                //         return (x, y) switch { (1, 2) => 3 };
                Diagnostic(ErrorCode.WRN_SwitchExpressionNotExhaustive, "switch").WithLocation(17, 23)
                );
            CompileAndVerify(compilation, expectedOutput: @"3
MatchFailureException()");
        }
```

Note that the exception throw in this case does not contain the `UnmatchedValue` that was input to the switch expression.  The reason the compiler does not pass that tuple to the exception constructor is that the compiler never constructs the tuple at all.  Rather the compiler produces the decision tree based on the individual values that were the input.  Because of that the generated code does not even have a runtime dependence on the presence of the `ValueTuple` library.

This is consistent with the [design of the `MatchFailureException` type](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/issues/33284) and the LDM's specification that the captured value shall be provided when it is "trivial" to do so.  However, it would be possible for the compiler to produce code that constructs the tuple just for the failure case, at the expense of causing the code to depend on the `ValueTuple` library at runtime.

This is a tracking issue while we seek guidance on how to handle this situation.

